00:02:45,801 --> 00:02:49,783
And as an effects department, we were really able to make a big difference for players

47
00:02:49,783 --> 00:02:53,886
with visual and cognitive needs with our contrast options.

48
00:02:53,886 --> 00:02:57,449
And lastly, we're just going to talk about challenges for new generation and some of

49
00:02:57,449 --> 00:02:59,910
the learnings and takeaways that we had while working on this project.

50
00:03:00,863 --> 00:03:04,344
So let's get into it. Let's start talking about Miles' Venom powers.

51
00:03:04,344 --> 00:03:09,387
They're central to the character and a pillar, a part of the pillar of creating an amazing new Spider-Man.

52
00:03:09,387 --> 00:03:15,289
So this is our next generation shot that we made for the PS5 reveal.

53
00:03:15,289 --> 00:03:22,192
And this is, in the scene we see Miles draining electricity from an overloading reactor.

54
00:03:22,192 --> 00:03:27,194
And as the camera moves across his arm, we see his suit peel away as his arm flashes with electricity.

55
00:03:28,315 --> 00:03:32,197
And as the camera continues, his mask eventually disintegrates as well,

56
00:03:32,197 --> 00:03:34,177
revealing who he is to the player.

57
00:03:34,177 --> 00:03:39,800
And for these shots, we really had to figure out creating a soft body simulation pipeline,

58
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:42,901
just so that we could get that suit disintegrating and coming apart.

59
00:03:42,901 --> 00:03:46,463
We also had to figure out how we were going to get that X-ray kind of effect on his skin,

60
00:03:46,463 --> 00:03:49,944
so you can kind of see his bones and his viscera through that.

61
00:03:49,944 --> 00:03:53,445
We also had to work on the glass particles flying at the camera,

62
00:03:53,445 --> 00:03:55,606
and of course the suit burning up.

63
00:03:56,307 --> 00:04:01,909
So these were all challenges that we were eager to dive into as an effects team.

64
00:04:01,909 --> 00:04:05,750
So when we kind of started on this, this was really just a pitch on paper.

65
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:10,012
We had this really beautiful script that was written for this that honestly sent chills down

66
00:04:10,012 --> 00:04:16,434
my spine. All we really had was this piece of concept art and the script. And, you know,

67
00:04:16,434 --> 00:04:22,397
in this script, we hear Peter Parker talking to the player and telling the player, you know,

68
00:04:22,397 --> 00:04:24,637
Miles, this is your chance to go be a hero.

69
00:04:25,938 --> 00:04:29,619
And that script, it sort of described,

70
00:04:29,619 --> 00:04:32,180
we sort of see Miles put his hands into the reactor.

71
00:04:32,180 --> 00:04:35,101
We see him absorb this power into himself.

72
00:04:35,101 --> 00:04:37,322
And this is really his defining moment as a hero.

73
00:04:37,322 --> 00:04:41,904
This is where Miles decides to save his neighborhood

74
00:04:41,904 --> 00:04:43,724
within New York City.

75
00:04:43,724 --> 00:04:46,965
And it's a moment of self-sacrifice

76
00:04:46,965 --> 00:04:49,366
because as he absorbs this into himself,

77
00:04:49,366 --> 00:04:50,367
it's a really dangerous moment

78
00:04:50,367 --> 00:04:51,227
where he could potentially die.

79
00:04:52,407 --> 00:04:56,028
So when I heard this script, I mean, it honestly sent chills down my spine.

80
00:04:56,028 --> 00:05:00,469
This was a huge opportunity for the effects team to sort of push ourselves

81
00:05:00,469 --> 00:05:01,909
and to create something new and amazing.

82
00:05:01,909 --> 00:05:05,650
However, I was also really nervous when I heard it because, you know,

83
00:05:05,650 --> 00:05:08,211
we didn't have the tools to pull it off.

84
00:05:08,211 --> 00:05:10,511
We had to develop those along the way.

85
00:05:10,511 --> 00:05:15,973
So one of the big problems that we needed really high-quality Venom electricity,

86
00:05:15,973 --> 00:05:18,713
so that electricity that crackles down his arm,

87
00:05:18,713 --> 00:05:21,514
that's something that we had to develop for this.

88
00:05:22,294 --> 00:05:27,158
We have a little bit of electricity, it's biological, and it's something that comes

89
00:05:27,158 --> 00:05:27,679
from Miles himself.

90
00:05:27,679 --> 00:05:33,503
And this really differentiates him from Peter Parker, the Spider-Man in our previous game,

91
00:05:33,503 --> 00:05:38,107
Marvel's Spider-Man, because his abilities are more technology-based.

92
00:05:38,107 --> 00:05:41,390
We also had to figure out how to do soft-body simulations.

93
00:05:41,390 --> 00:05:46,574
We didn't really have a pipeline to be able to do things like simulations of fabric tearing

94
00:05:46,574 --> 00:05:46,714
off.

95
00:05:47,677 --> 00:05:50,178
So that was the question we were asking ourselves,

96
00:05:50,178 --> 00:05:52,079
was, OK, well, we really want to do this.

97
00:05:52,079 --> 00:05:53,299
We think it's really, really cool.

98
00:05:53,299 --> 00:05:54,660
How are we going to pull this off?

99
00:05:54,660 --> 00:05:58,822
So just so everybody watching at home understands,

100
00:05:58,822 --> 00:06:02,204
when it comes to this shot, the effects team

101
00:06:02,204 --> 00:06:04,185
was responsible for a great deal of it.

102
00:06:04,185 --> 00:06:05,726
When you remove the character from the equation,

103
00:06:05,726 --> 00:06:08,607
you can really kind of see the soft body simulation

104
00:06:08,607 --> 00:06:11,008
in question, as well as the glass particulates.

105
00:06:12,269 --> 00:06:16,673
the electricity that kind of crawls down. We need to do that for both arms of course.

106
00:06:16,673 --> 00:06:20,997
And you know, since I took the character out, you can't see it, but there's also that sort of

107
00:06:20,997 --> 00:06:24,781
x-ray effect that's going on on the character. So you can kind of see his bones and his viscera

108
00:06:24,781 --> 00:06:29,305
inside of his body, because it's really important for Miles as a character that this is coming from him.

109
00:06:30,747 --> 00:06:35,413
So, some of the solutions that we came up with to pull this off, we ended up leaning

110
00:06:35,413 --> 00:06:37,956
on some current-gen techniques to start.

111
00:06:37,956 --> 00:06:41,821
We painted vertex colors to drive that sort of slow reveal of the electricity.

112
00:06:41,821 --> 00:06:47,568
Our artist, Jenna, did a pass on this and she did an amazing job on creating this electricity.

113
00:06:48,189 --> 00:06:51,632
So one of the things we found was that we could afford more vertices on next gen.

114
00:06:51,632 --> 00:06:54,835
And we really tried to use that to our advantage where we could.

115
00:06:54,835 --> 00:06:59,379
By using more vertices, we were able to sort of push that fidelity on the next gen console.

116
00:06:59,379 --> 00:07:04,164
And we were also able to use the, you know, everybody's sort of used this technique,

117
00:07:04,164 --> 00:07:09,048
I'm sure, where you use vertex colors, you color a vertice, like red, green, or blue.

118
00:07:09,048 --> 00:07:10,409
In this case, I think we used red.

119
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:14,933
just to be able to drive that precise wipe.

120
00:07:14,933 --> 00:07:17,095
So there's material nodes in our material editor,

121
00:07:17,095 --> 00:07:19,917
vertex color nodes, that we sort of lean

122
00:07:19,917 --> 00:07:20,958
into to be able to drive this.

123
00:07:20,958 --> 00:07:23,360
This is kind of what that looks like in the particle editor.

124
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:26,482
So as you can see, we were able to get

125
00:07:26,482 --> 00:07:29,224
like a lot of precise control, kind of leveraging

126
00:07:29,224 --> 00:07:30,806
a current gen technique.

127
00:07:30,806 --> 00:07:33,528
In addition to that, we also layered on some

128
00:07:33,528 --> 00:07:35,169
of those little particle quads.

129
00:07:35,169 --> 00:07:36,930
So you're able to sort of see.

130
00:07:37,751 --> 00:07:42,434
those additional tertiary lightenings at the ends.

131
00:07:42,434 --> 00:07:47,938
So we did layer in some particle quads in addition to using meshes.

132
00:07:47,938 --> 00:07:52,801
But I really liked that we were able to essentially model this out to get more fidelity for this shot.

133
00:07:54,726 --> 00:07:59,469
Next up, we're going to talk about simulations and what we call our Anamvert pipeline.

134
00:07:59,469 --> 00:08:05,133
So we needed to develop a pipeline for bringing in baked soft body simulations that really

135
00:08:05,133 --> 00:08:06,854
didn't exist in Marvel's Spider-Man.

136
00:08:06,854 --> 00:08:11,237
Our solution for this was the Anamvert pipeline.

137
00:08:11,237 --> 00:08:14,680
The Anamvert pipeline can support tens of thousands of soft body polygons.

138
00:08:15,460 --> 00:08:18,221
So this is kind of what this ends up looking like.

139
00:08:18,221 --> 00:08:24,683
This is something that our artist Matthew simulated in Houdini and exported out of Maya.

140
00:08:24,683 --> 00:08:26,504
This is actually taken from Maya.

141
00:08:26,504 --> 00:08:31,825
But we were able to support 29,000 verts, which I thought was pretty awesome and impressive

142
00:08:31,825 --> 00:08:33,966
for this next-gen shot.

143
00:08:34,466 --> 00:08:37,107
And this AnimVert pipeline,

144
00:08:37,107 --> 00:08:38,787
we sort of had a prototype version of it,

145
00:08:38,787 --> 00:08:40,287
but we really fleshed this out

146
00:08:40,287 --> 00:08:41,647
and finished it out for our trailer.

147
00:08:41,647 --> 00:08:43,968
And we really gained some useful new technology

148
00:08:43,968 --> 00:08:46,829
that we were able to leverage in other parts of the game.

149
00:08:46,829 --> 00:08:50,729
So just a huge credit to our entire programming staff,

150
00:08:50,729 --> 00:08:53,270
especially our animation programmers

151
00:08:53,270 --> 00:08:56,111
who were able to help us flesh out this pipeline,

152
00:08:56,111 --> 00:08:57,751
because I'm really just impressed

153
00:08:57,751 --> 00:09:00,211
that we were able to pull this together for this trailer.

154
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:05,251
And then we also used paint vertex weights

155
00:09:05,251 --> 00:09:07,672
to drive the burning edges of the sleeve.

156
00:09:07,672 --> 00:09:08,513
So it was really important for us

157
00:09:08,513 --> 00:09:09,793
when we were working on this shot

158
00:09:09,793 --> 00:09:12,154
to have the audience reveal and understand

159
00:09:12,154 --> 00:09:13,655
who Miles is while they're watching it.

160
00:09:13,655 --> 00:09:16,676
So as the camera is moving,

161
00:09:16,676 --> 00:09:18,497
you're not entirely sure who it is

162
00:09:18,497 --> 00:09:21,338
until the camera starts pulling up closer and closer

163
00:09:21,338 --> 00:09:24,599
and you see, oh, at the end it's Miles.

164
00:09:24,599 --> 00:09:25,379
It's who Miles is.

165
00:09:25,379 --> 00:09:29,341
So what we did was we sort of used vertex color again here.

166
00:09:29,901 --> 00:09:33,763
We just sort of painted using the red channel to drive that erosion.

167
00:09:33,763 --> 00:09:36,785
So this is actually a GIF.

168
00:09:36,785 --> 00:09:42,089
It moves pretty slowly because this shot took place over the course of a couple seconds.

169
00:09:42,089 --> 00:09:47,232
But using that red channel, we're sort of able to erode out the simulated chunks.

170
00:09:48,193 --> 00:09:54,655
And then also by using an additional color channel, in this case the green channel, we're able to erode out,

171
00:09:54,655 --> 00:09:59,837
we're able to put that hot burning erosion edge in addition to eroding out the alpha.

172
00:09:59,837 --> 00:10:05,338
So that's kind of how we were able to layer those together to create that soot burning up effect.

173
00:10:06,859 --> 00:10:11,043
Next, I'd like to talk about that X-ray skin effect that Miles has.

174
00:10:11,043 --> 00:10:19,591
So this is a sort of a rotating GIF of his arm meshes and it sort of highlights his bones

175
00:10:19,591 --> 00:10:21,773
and tissue and viscera.

176
00:10:21,773 --> 00:10:27,719
And these sort of reveal in that sequence, they kind of flash on at certain points.

177
00:10:28,480 --> 00:10:32,482
And we drove this through something called Parallax Occlusion Maps.

178
00:10:32,482 --> 00:10:38,346
But this was a really important part of expressing who Miles is as a character

179
00:10:38,346 --> 00:10:42,748
through visual effects, because this is really a power that's coming from inside

180
00:10:42,748 --> 00:10:47,551
of him. We thought it was important that, you know, the audience and the viewer be

181
00:10:47,551 --> 00:10:49,092
able to see inside of him.

182
00:10:49,092 --> 00:10:49,352
So.

183
00:10:49,412 --> 00:10:54,036
This is his skin texture that we use to drive those parallax occlusion maps.

184
00:10:54,036 --> 00:10:58,160
This is sort of a current-gen technique. I'm sure many of you have used gray packs before.

185
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:04,666
I've also heard this called texture packing, but it's simply where you put different materials

186
00:11:04,666 --> 00:11:07,929
inside of your red, green, and blue channels because you really only care about that

187
00:11:07,929 --> 00:11:09,930
black and white information on those channels.

188
00:11:12,119 --> 00:11:15,925
So basically, we use parallax occlusion mapping

189
00:11:15,925 --> 00:11:17,688
for bones and veins.

190
00:11:17,688 --> 00:11:19,271
That's essentially kind of like a height map

191
00:11:19,271 --> 00:11:21,856
that doesn't displace the surface of an object.

192
00:11:21,856 --> 00:11:22,978
We use it to fake depth.

193
00:11:24,362 --> 00:11:27,705
It technically uses ray marching and it is expensive.

194
00:11:27,705 --> 00:11:30,167
And it's sort of painted and authored like height maps.

195
00:11:30,167 --> 00:11:31,769
But parallax occlusion maps, I mean,

196
00:11:31,769 --> 00:11:33,950
you essentially want to use these any time

197
00:11:33,950 --> 00:11:36,553
where you really want to get that sort of fake depth.

198
00:11:36,553 --> 00:11:39,015
It's really good for kind of pushing downwards.

199
00:11:39,015 --> 00:11:40,496
It's really good for craters,

200
00:11:40,496 --> 00:11:42,238
but we kind of saw an opportunity here.

201
00:11:42,238 --> 00:11:45,561
This was actually one of our artists, Jenna's ideas,

202
00:11:45,561 --> 00:11:47,322
just to be able to use it to fake depth on a character.

203
00:11:47,322 --> 00:11:50,525
So you can kind of see the inside of them.

204
00:11:52,274 --> 00:11:59,656
So, at least when it comes to the material graph, the parallax occlusion maps are actually

205
00:11:59,656 --> 00:12:02,597
these UV modifiers that go into the UV texture.

206
00:12:02,597 --> 00:12:08,958
So you can kind of see here the parallax occlusion information is kind of going into that UV channel.

207
00:12:08,958 --> 00:12:13,379
And you know, on the blue channel, we're using that blue channel texture to drive just some

208
00:12:13,379 --> 00:12:15,040
of the cloudy noise inside of miles.

209
00:12:15,700 --> 00:12:19,909
We're using the red channel to drive some of the squiggly veins inside of his arms and

210
00:12:19,909 --> 00:12:23,275
then the green channel is the one that's primarily being used for his bones.

211
00:12:23,275 --> 00:12:24,017
And then...

212
00:12:26,069 --> 00:12:28,231
This is just another example of this.

213
00:12:28,231 --> 00:12:31,174
We're using more parallax occlusion

214
00:12:31,174 --> 00:12:34,317
to drive that squiggly look.

215
00:12:34,317 --> 00:12:36,920
So we actually are using some UV translate in this as well,

216
00:12:36,920 --> 00:12:40,123
so that as it's moving, you get some additional motion.

217
00:12:40,123 --> 00:12:44,187
So you can see that UV parallax occlusion, UV modifier

218
00:12:44,187 --> 00:12:48,331
feeding into the UV translate nodes on the bottom.

219
00:12:48,331 --> 00:12:49,312
And this is a

220
00:12:50,233 --> 00:12:55,261
you know, just a really useful technique to kind of get some additional motion into the depth

221
00:12:55,261 --> 00:12:59,608
just by using some UV translate nodes to sort of get that additional motion.

222
00:13:01,836 --> 00:13:04,657
Next, I kind of want to talk about Mega Venom Blast.

223
00:13:04,657 --> 00:13:09,898
So this is sort of the penultimate venom power that Miles has.

224
00:13:09,898 --> 00:13:13,279
And it was really important to us as we were working on this that it looked like the comic

225
00:13:13,279 --> 00:13:13,859
books.

226
00:13:13,859 --> 00:13:18,740
It's also biological in nature, so this is something that comes from inside of Miles.

227
00:13:18,740 --> 00:13:22,021
This differentiates him from Peter Parker, who uses more technical gadgets.

228
00:13:23,041 --> 00:13:25,442
It was important for us that it felt web-like.

229
00:13:25,442 --> 00:13:29,343
So this is something that is Spider-Man's electricity.

230
00:13:29,343 --> 00:13:32,484
This is not, you know, Electro's electricity.

231
00:13:32,484 --> 00:13:35,846
This isn't the electricity of some other hero.

232
00:13:35,846 --> 00:13:37,146
It also needs to work in 360 degrees.

233
00:13:37,146 --> 00:13:41,468
So we really need to be able to see this mesh in gameplay.

234
00:13:42,344 --> 00:13:47,590
And this is really the ultimate in Miles's powers and the expression of himself.

235
00:13:47,590 --> 00:13:51,975
And it really needs to support our game pillar of an explosive new Spider-Man.

236
00:13:51,975 --> 00:13:56,361
So this was one of my favorite pieces of art

237
00:13:56,361 --> 00:13:58,223
of Mega Venom Blast from the Marvel Comics.

238
00:13:58,843 --> 00:14:02,905
You can kind of see here it has that really nice sort of graphical look.

239
00:14:02,905 --> 00:14:05,186
Spider-Man is just in the air.

240
00:14:05,186 --> 00:14:08,728
And as he's letting this power out of himself,

241
00:14:08,728 --> 00:14:11,289
it sort of explodes into this web shape.

242
00:14:11,289 --> 00:14:13,310
And this was a really powerful image.

243
00:14:13,310 --> 00:14:16,111
And, you know, it's really a challenge when you're looking at something like this.

244
00:14:16,111 --> 00:14:21,013
It obviously works really well in the 2D sort of graphic state.

245
00:14:21,013 --> 00:14:23,794
But, you know, the question we have to ask ourselves as real time effects artists

246
00:14:23,794 --> 00:14:24,255
is, OK, well,

247
00:14:24,515 --> 00:14:26,797
This is wonderful, I love looking at this.

248
00:14:26,797 --> 00:14:29,920
How do I get this to translate into three dimensions?

249
00:14:29,920 --> 00:14:34,184
So this was the one that we ended up having

250
00:14:34,184 --> 00:14:35,685
in the end on our game.

251
00:14:35,685 --> 00:14:38,248
As you can see, it goes out in 360 degrees.

252
00:14:38,248 --> 00:14:42,051
We have a little electricity on miles

253
00:14:42,051 --> 00:14:43,533
and then he jumps up in the air

254
00:14:43,533 --> 00:14:45,174
and he does this mega venom blast.

255
00:14:45,174 --> 00:14:47,116
It does have that kind of web shape to it.

256
00:14:48,059 --> 00:14:55,321
We layer in a couple of different particle quads as well as this large venom mesh that we use to sort of drive that look.

257
00:14:55,321 --> 00:14:58,282
So this is sort of what that looks like in our editor.

258
00:14:58,282 --> 00:15:03,643
And as you can see, we use quads, sparks, we have an effects light on there.

259
00:15:03,643 --> 00:15:07,204
I believe on the PlayStation 5 version that light is also a shadow caster.

260
00:15:07,204 --> 00:15:12,766
We have all these elements sort of working together along with this 360 degree web mesh.

261
00:15:13,666 --> 00:15:17,489
So when you look at the mesh by itself, when you isolate that,

262
00:15:17,489 --> 00:15:20,892
this is really the heart of MegaVenom Blast and that explosion.

263
00:15:20,892 --> 00:15:25,056
And it's driven by this mesh that we used,

264
00:15:25,056 --> 00:15:28,439
and we found that we could use more vertices on next-gen especially.

265
00:15:28,439 --> 00:15:32,402
But it's driven by this mesh, and it's driven by a material sort of coursing through it.

266
00:15:32,402 --> 00:15:34,944
At the end of the day, I mean, it's a relatively simple technique,

267
00:15:34,944 --> 00:15:37,707
but what makes it effective is that we have

268
00:15:37,707 --> 00:15:40,469
more fidelity on this mesh than what we could have on previous generations.

269
00:15:41,470 --> 00:15:43,451
So this is what that looks like in Maya.

270
00:15:43,451 --> 00:15:45,273
This is just the mesh in question for Maya.

271
00:15:45,273 --> 00:15:48,535
And really, we kind of fight on next generation platforms

272
00:15:48,535 --> 00:15:51,897
that we can utilize meshes more thoroughly.

273
00:15:51,897 --> 00:15:54,559
And I'm really hoping that for anyone looking at home,

274
00:15:54,559 --> 00:15:56,521
you know, just wondering how can I push visual effects

275
00:15:56,521 --> 00:15:57,181
for the next generation?

276
00:15:58,042 --> 00:16:00,884
you know, you consider just using more meshes,

277
00:16:00,884 --> 00:16:03,706
you can probably get more fidelity in your visuals that way.

278
00:16:03,706 --> 00:16:05,928
The other benefit to building effects in this way

279
00:16:05,928 --> 00:16:07,990
is that it also sort of minimizes overdraw.

280
00:16:07,990 --> 00:16:11,612
So, you know, when you have more of this negative space

281
00:16:11,612 --> 00:16:14,374
that's actually negative space and not, you know,

282
00:16:14,374 --> 00:16:15,876
just alphaing out on materials,

283
00:16:15,876 --> 00:16:18,778
it kind of saves performance in a different way.

284
00:16:18,778 --> 00:16:20,359
I mean, it is more expensive on the vertices side,

285
00:16:20,359 --> 00:16:22,481
but you're not really paying those overdraw costs

286
00:16:22,481 --> 00:16:24,262
that you would pay if this was all quads.

287
00:16:26,234 --> 00:16:28,175
Next, I want to talk about the venom sleeve.

288
00:16:28,175 --> 00:16:34,616
So one of the things that we had to figure out was having electricity crawl down Miles'

289
00:16:34,616 --> 00:16:34,916
arm.

290
00:16:34,916 --> 00:16:39,257
This was, and it was really important that it felt biological, that it was kind of, you

291
00:16:39,257 --> 00:16:42,058
know, inside of him, that it was coming from him.

292
00:16:42,058 --> 00:16:44,918
So this is different from Peter's technical gadgets.

293
00:16:44,918 --> 00:16:47,299
So Miles has his own Spider-Man.

294
00:16:47,299 --> 00:16:53,000
He is sort of generating the power from within, whereas Peter Parker creates gadgets.

295
00:16:53,561 --> 00:16:55,942
So we really had to ask ourselves,

296
00:16:55,942 --> 00:16:58,484
how can we get this Venom electricity

297
00:16:58,484 --> 00:17:01,066
that comes from within Miles Morales

298
00:17:01,066 --> 00:17:02,807
working on all of his suits?

299
00:17:02,807 --> 00:17:03,988
And how can we get it looking good?

300
00:17:03,988 --> 00:17:06,270
Because one consideration with the Spider-Man games

301
00:17:06,270 --> 00:17:08,871
is that the player can unlock different suits.

302
00:17:08,871 --> 00:17:11,333
They all have different silhouettes

303
00:17:11,333 --> 00:17:12,354
and different shapes to them.

304
00:17:12,354 --> 00:17:15,056
So, you know, we really needed something

305
00:17:15,056 --> 00:17:17,558
that would fit very, very closely,

306
00:17:17,558 --> 00:17:19,959
you know, basically be inside of the mesh.

307
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:24,464
as well as give us that fidelity across different suits.

308
00:17:24,464 --> 00:17:26,146
So I think this is one of my favorite examples

309
00:17:26,146 --> 00:17:28,228
of the venom sleeve in action.

310
00:17:28,228 --> 00:17:32,592
This is kind of right before that large reactor shot

311
00:17:32,592 --> 00:17:34,314
that we already talked about.

