00:17:34,314 --> 00:17:36,176
But here, Miles is absorbing that reactor energy

313
00:17:36,176 --> 00:17:36,796
into himself.

314
00:17:37,657 --> 00:17:43,302
and we also sort of use color storytelling in here. This was actually one of our artists,

315
00:17:43,302 --> 00:17:49,487
Jenna's idea, but as Miles is taking this blue new form of electricity into himself, it changes

316
00:17:49,487 --> 00:17:55,592
into yellow venom electricity as he can train, gets mastery over it. Some other details in here

317
00:17:55,592 --> 00:17:58,794
that I really liked that we did, if you look closely at his rib cage, you might see

318
00:17:59,575 --> 00:18:03,878
like a bit of a silhouette of a rib cage in there. Also his skin is kind of flashing again

319
00:18:03,878 --> 00:18:08,601
with some parallax occlusion. You can kind of see hints at his skull just to sort of give that

320
00:18:08,601 --> 00:18:15,205
feeling of you know this is really affecting him and this is a really big moment in the

321
00:18:15,205 --> 00:18:20,088
narrative as his moment of sacrifice. So the way that we sort of did the venom sleeve

322
00:18:20,997 --> 00:18:26,261
We created this mesh that goes over all of Spider-Man's suits.

323
00:18:26,261 --> 00:18:28,923
So it's something that our character team ended up

324
00:18:28,923 --> 00:18:30,944
modeling and skinning and implementing

325
00:18:30,944 --> 00:18:33,206
on all of the different suits.

326
00:18:33,206 --> 00:18:35,168
Then we just sort of had a universal texture

327
00:18:35,168 --> 00:18:38,330
that a material set with different wipes

328
00:18:38,330 --> 00:18:42,433
is sort of applied to all of those same meshes.

329
00:18:42,433 --> 00:18:44,115
We also worked with our gameplay team

330
00:18:44,115 --> 00:18:46,817
so that this suit isn't technically on.

331
00:18:47,357 --> 00:18:52,585
all the time, mostly because we found that it got expensive to have all that alpha on the character at all times.

332
00:18:52,585 --> 00:18:57,532
So our gameplay team very carefully, cleverly put this into look groups so that

333
00:18:57,532 --> 00:19:00,997
we were able to turn this on when we needed to and turned it off when we didn't need it.

334
00:19:02,037 --> 00:19:06,119
This is kind of similar to the Parallax Occlusion maps

335
00:19:06,119 --> 00:19:08,260
with like the bones and the viscera.

336
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:11,521
We use a gray pack texture here to drive the different veins

337
00:19:11,521 --> 00:19:13,202
for the Venom Sleeve reveal.

338
00:19:13,202 --> 00:19:16,344
So that was just really beneficial

339
00:19:16,344 --> 00:19:19,845
because as this was a cross-platform title,

340
00:19:19,845 --> 00:19:21,226
we found that texture memory

341
00:19:21,226 --> 00:19:24,148
is still a concern on PS4 especially.

342
00:19:24,148 --> 00:19:26,389
But this was still a useful technique on PS5 as well.

343
00:19:27,930 --> 00:19:31,392
So we basically split those different visceral channels out

344
00:19:31,392 --> 00:19:36,516
into, you know, we use our red, green, and blue channels separately.

345
00:19:36,516 --> 00:19:39,698
You know, and here we have the mirrored texture

346
00:19:39,698 --> 00:19:43,681
kind of being split, and we can sort of select the left and the right side of it.

347
00:19:43,681 --> 00:19:47,403
And then here are sort of the controls that sort of drive that

348
00:19:47,403 --> 00:19:51,486
wipe. The progression node in the bottom left, that's sort of the main

349
00:19:51,486 --> 00:19:55,409
driver that we use most of the time for driving this

350
00:19:55,409 --> 00:19:56,450
reveal over time.

351
00:19:57,070 --> 00:20:02,494
It's supposed to be a gameplay team who has control over how fast or slow that needs to be,

352
00:20:02,494 --> 00:20:04,976
depending on when and where we're using it.

353
00:20:04,976 --> 00:20:10,619
We also have some additional knobs in here for some key moments where we need to tweak the speed of Venom.

354
00:20:11,732 --> 00:20:16,975
So another thing that we did within the venom sleeve that we found to be very beneficial

355
00:20:16,975 --> 00:20:21,477
was using a displacement, just a little bit of displacement to prevent clipping.

356
00:20:21,477 --> 00:20:26,820
So that was kind of helpful to ensure that the sleeve works on all of Miles' suits.

357
00:20:26,820 --> 00:20:30,322
So anytime he bends his elbow or deforms his shoulder,

358
00:20:30,322 --> 00:20:34,024
by offsetting a little bit in the material and by pushing it a little bit toward the camera,

359
00:20:34,584 --> 00:20:39,147
we're really able to prevent any clipping and to make sure that this is properly visible at all

360
00:20:39,147 --> 00:20:44,051
times. Another place where this is useful is also in the fingers, just because there might be a lot

361
00:20:44,051 --> 00:20:49,514
of clipping there. All right, so thanks for talking to me with me about Venom powers. Now we're going

362
00:20:49,514 --> 00:20:54,658
to move on to camouflage and invisibility, which is another one of Miles's key powers.

363
00:20:54,658 --> 00:21:00,702
So this is an early piece of concept art. This kind of shows Miles turning invisible.

364
00:21:00,702 --> 00:21:03,124
So there's a lot of things in here that we ended up...

365
00:21:03,624 --> 00:21:06,866
using in the final version of Camouflage.

366
00:21:06,866 --> 00:21:09,627
Things like the fact that he's tinted a little bit blue,

367
00:21:09,627 --> 00:21:12,549
he's invisible, of course, he has a fresnel on him,

368
00:21:12,549 --> 00:21:15,910
he has the chromatic aberration inside of his body.

369
00:21:15,910 --> 00:21:17,451
We didn't end up using everything in here.

370
00:21:17,451 --> 00:21:19,752
We didn't make the enemies red,

371
00:21:19,752 --> 00:21:21,833
we didn't really do a full screen effect,

372
00:21:21,833 --> 00:21:22,994
like what's in this concept.

373
00:21:22,994 --> 00:21:24,835
But a lot of these early ideas

374
00:21:24,835 --> 00:21:26,676
did end up making it into the game.

375
00:21:28,076 --> 00:21:29,916
And this is the in-game version.

376
00:21:29,916 --> 00:21:32,377
So this is sort of where Miles turns fully invisible.

377
00:21:32,377 --> 00:21:35,357
And this basically took us three different materials

378
00:21:35,357 --> 00:21:36,238
to pull off.

379
00:21:36,238 --> 00:21:39,218
The chromatic aberration that was in that earlier concept

380
00:21:39,218 --> 00:21:41,119
is something that you can also see here.

381
00:21:41,119 --> 00:21:43,619
So you can really see that the green and the red channels,

382
00:21:43,619 --> 00:21:45,119
especially if you look at the windows

383
00:21:45,119 --> 00:21:46,080
and the distance through Miles,

384
00:21:46,080 --> 00:21:49,080
you can really kind of see that those are a little bit offset

385
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:50,300
from each other.

386
00:21:50,300 --> 00:21:52,921
And you can also kind of see that a bit on the snow

387
00:21:52,921 --> 00:21:54,021
through his legs,

388
00:21:54,021 --> 00:21:55,701
but I think it's most prominent on those windows.

389
00:21:56,242 --> 00:22:00,545
There's also that transition, so he kind of starts fully opaque,

390
00:22:00,545 --> 00:22:05,228
and he sort of gets that kind of like patchwork transition where he turns invisible.

391
00:22:05,228 --> 00:22:10,592
So the way that we sort of pulled this effect off, we used some things called precomposite

392
00:22:10,592 --> 00:22:16,336
and postcomposite materials to drive that transition. Precomposite materials are materials

393
00:22:16,336 --> 00:22:21,120
that erode out of mesh, so these sort of tell the pixels to not be drawn. And those are applied,

394
00:22:21,120 --> 00:22:24,562
like if you think about your render order, those are applied basically before the materials are

395
00:22:24,562 --> 00:22:24,902
drawn.

396
00:22:25,503 --> 00:22:30,046
The post composites are materials that apply after the main material is drawn.

397
00:22:30,046 --> 00:22:35,410
So the post composites are materials that basically in the render order we draw everything

398
00:22:35,410 --> 00:22:36,991
we put the post composites on after.

399
00:22:36,991 --> 00:22:40,293
So that's how you can kind of think about pre's before post is after.

400
00:22:40,293 --> 00:22:42,634
That's why they're called pre and post composites.

401
00:22:43,055 --> 00:22:45,175
In general, these materials are really useful

402
00:22:45,175 --> 00:22:48,296
because we can apply them over entire meshes

403
00:22:48,296 --> 00:22:50,276
without them being material overrides.

404
00:22:50,276 --> 00:22:51,176
So they're reusable.

405
00:22:51,176 --> 00:22:53,537
We can put them on all sorts of objects in the game.

406
00:22:53,537 --> 00:22:57,318
You know, they're something that we utilize a lot

407
00:22:57,318 --> 00:22:58,538
in our workflows.

408
00:22:58,538 --> 00:23:00,058
And the camouflage effect,

409
00:23:00,058 --> 00:23:03,259
it required both a pre and post composite shader

410
00:23:03,259 --> 00:23:05,839
where after the transition is complete,

411
00:23:05,839 --> 00:23:07,920
then we go to a complete material swap

412
00:23:07,920 --> 00:23:08,520
and take a sip of water.

413
00:23:13,572 --> 00:23:16,114
So this is the precomposite material.

414
00:23:16,114 --> 00:23:20,038
You can kind of see the alpha erodes out.

415
00:23:20,038 --> 00:23:23,661
It erodes out the mesh before the pixels are fully drawn.

416
00:23:23,661 --> 00:23:27,083
So with the precomposite, this is sort of a yes, no,

417
00:23:27,083 --> 00:23:29,846
is there, is not there kind of setup.

418
00:23:29,846 --> 00:23:31,867
We don't really have like a shades of gray width

419
00:23:31,867 --> 00:23:34,189
and that's just sort of because of where it sort of comes

420
00:23:34,189 --> 00:23:35,590
in the material rendering order.

421
00:23:35,590 --> 00:23:38,393
However, it's still really useful for cases like this

422
00:23:38,393 --> 00:23:40,975
where we want to fully erode out somebody.

423
00:23:41,963 --> 00:23:44,567
This was the post-composite material.

424
00:23:44,567 --> 00:23:49,694
You'll notice that the erosion pattern on it, this mirrors the erosion pattern in the

425
00:23:49,694 --> 00:23:50,636
pre-composite material.

426
00:23:50,636 --> 00:23:54,842
So they're basically the same except the post-composite is inverse.

427
00:23:54,842 --> 00:23:59,027
So as the pre-composite erodes out, the post-composite erodes in.

428
00:23:59,671 --> 00:24:06,039
And it contains similar shading information to the main shader that has that chromatic aberration in it.

429
00:24:06,039 --> 00:24:07,581
You know, it's blue, it has that fresnel.

430
00:24:07,581 --> 00:24:09,584
The math is basically the same between those two,

431
00:24:09,584 --> 00:24:12,748
except the post-composite also has that erosion information

432
00:24:12,748 --> 00:24:16,854
because it's used for that transition between the solid and the invisible state.

433
00:24:17,735 --> 00:24:22,537
Once the erosion is complete, we do a swap at that point for the main invisibility shader.

434
00:24:22,537 --> 00:24:28,700
And the reason why we do that is because having the pre and post composite shaders is more expensive.

435
00:24:28,700 --> 00:24:32,962
If you do that whole material swap, that ends up being cheaper, and that was more performant.

436
00:24:32,962 --> 00:24:37,644
And because this was a cross-generation title especially, we needed to make sure that it ran in frame on the PS4.

437
00:24:37,644 --> 00:24:41,186
And then this basically...

438
00:24:42,887 --> 00:24:44,948
applies over the pre-composite when you do that swap.

439
00:24:44,948 --> 00:24:50,232
It allows for the illusion where milestones are visible while also having solid parts.

440
00:24:50,232 --> 00:24:51,853
So when we set this up,

441
00:24:51,853 --> 00:24:54,776
our gameplay programming team is wonderful.

442
00:24:54,776 --> 00:24:57,337
They set up these configs for us so that we can

443
00:24:57,337 --> 00:25:00,740
implement our effects into the game using them.

444
00:25:00,740 --> 00:25:03,162
So we did need some help

445
00:25:03,162 --> 00:25:05,443
from our friendly neighborhood programmers to make this happen.

446
00:25:06,426 --> 00:25:09,308
And then, oh yeah, chromatic aberration.

447
00:25:09,308 --> 00:25:15,313
So the chromatic aberration is really driven by offsetting the red and the green channels

448
00:25:15,313 --> 00:25:16,694
from each other on the frame buffer.

449
00:25:16,694 --> 00:25:18,615
So you can kind of see we have two frame grabs there.

450
00:25:18,615 --> 00:25:22,458
They're eventually being combined into one where the red is being combined separately

451
00:25:22,458 --> 00:25:23,899
from the green and blue of the other.

452
00:25:24,400 --> 00:25:32,885
frame buffer. And then, you know, earlier on in the math, we're just offsetting one of them

453
00:25:32,885 --> 00:25:38,569
by like 0.01 and we're offsetting the other by negative 0.01. So those offsets are just a little

454
00:25:38,569 --> 00:25:43,553
bit, you only really need a little bit, and then that ends up being combined in the end to create

455
00:25:43,553 --> 00:25:44,553
some chromatic aberration.

456
00:25:45,582 --> 00:25:52,901
So we also found as we were working on camouflage that we needed some special one-off variants.

457
00:25:52,901 --> 00:25:54,625
So there were really some...

458
00:25:55,457 --> 00:25:58,959
cases in the game where Miles had these emotional beats,

459
00:25:58,959 --> 00:26:04,902
and originally we didn't set up camo to really have any other timing except for that zero to one.

460
00:26:04,902 --> 00:26:09,364
However, we really wanted to make sure that we were including these moments

461
00:26:09,364 --> 00:26:11,865
using visual effects to sort of help the player understand

462
00:26:11,865 --> 00:26:16,627
times where Miles was doubting himself or when he was scared or when he wanted to hide.

463
00:26:17,057 --> 00:26:20,961
And this required a few custom setups to make it happen,

464
00:26:20,961 --> 00:26:25,545
but it was totally worth it to help Miles become his own explosive new Spider-Man.

465
00:26:25,545 --> 00:26:30,569
So one such example, this is actually the first time that we see camouflage in-game.

466
00:26:30,569 --> 00:26:33,091
In this moment, Miles is threatened by Roxxon forces,

467
00:26:33,091 --> 00:26:37,816
and we had to slow down the camouflage transition to really make this feed feel good.

468
00:26:37,816 --> 00:26:41,279
So the transition is usually about a second long.

469
00:26:41,839 --> 00:26:44,541
And it's basically that zero to one parameter material

470
00:26:44,541 --> 00:26:46,022
we just talked about.

471
00:26:46,022 --> 00:26:49,544
But our programming team exposed some knobs for us

472
00:26:49,544 --> 00:26:53,227
in the cinematic so that we were able to really slow this down.

473
00:26:53,227 --> 00:26:54,988
And I love showing this beat too,

474
00:26:54,988 --> 00:26:57,990
because especially when the camera is looking right

475
00:26:57,990 --> 00:26:59,771
through miles at those ROXON officers,

476
00:26:59,771 --> 00:27:04,334
you can really see that chromatic aberration there.

477
00:27:06,021 --> 00:27:11,086
Another time where we had to do this was this moment where Miles, this is right after the

478
00:27:11,086 --> 00:27:15,732
bridge explodes, and he doubts himself as Spider-Man and he's not really able to control

479
00:27:15,732 --> 00:27:18,855
his camo powers, so his hand by itself turns invisible.

480
00:27:18,855 --> 00:27:25,883
And in order to get this beat, the camo ability was sort of designed to go over all...

481
00:27:26,444 --> 00:27:30,647
of the character. It wasn't really designed to go on one part of the character. So our character

482
00:27:30,647 --> 00:27:36,271
team sort of split that hand off to be its own mesh. And then we made a custom material, so the

483
00:27:36,271 --> 00:27:40,714
pre-composite material is really only eroding out his fingers. And this was really nice because it

484
00:27:40,714 --> 00:27:46,398
kind of gave Miles that moment where, you know, he's able to question himself before realizing

485
00:27:46,398 --> 00:27:48,760
that, yes, I am Spider-Man and I can do this.

486
00:27:50,164 --> 00:27:55,406
This was another camouflage beat that we did where Miles tries to disappear.

487
00:27:55,406 --> 00:28:02,050
This is right after he's captured and the Roxxon guards are hitting him.

488
00:28:02,050 --> 00:28:04,071
And we had to speed up camo in this beat.

489
00:28:04,071 --> 00:28:07,993
We had to make it really fast just so he could try to go invisible and then he'd get hit

490
00:28:07,993 --> 00:28:10,474
and then he would come out of it.

491
00:28:10,474 --> 00:28:15,176
And this is sort of building up right to the moment before we do our first mega venom blast.

492
00:28:15,176 --> 00:28:17,978
So it was a really fun beat to work on.

493
00:28:19,016 --> 00:28:21,819
All right, next we're going to talk about creating spectacle.

494
00:28:21,819 --> 00:28:23,801
So Marvel's Spider-Man Miles Morales

495
00:28:23,801 --> 00:28:27,125
is a game that really requires intensive spectacle beats

496
00:28:27,125 --> 00:28:30,128
so that Miles can demonstrate his heroic abilities.

497
00:28:30,128 --> 00:28:31,850
So one of the challenges that we asked ourselves

498
00:28:31,850 --> 00:28:33,332
while we were working on this was,

499
00:28:33,332 --> 00:28:35,154
how do we up this for a new generation

500
00:28:35,154 --> 00:28:37,256
for what we accomplished in Marvel's Spider-Man?

501
00:28:38,257 --> 00:28:42,759
One of the solutions to that was coming up with a new simulation pipeline.

502
00:28:42,759 --> 00:28:49,242
So, AnimChunk is our new rigid body pipeline, and we developed it to replace the previous pipeline we had in Marvel's Spider-Man.

503
00:28:49,242 --> 00:28:54,904
This new pipeline that we developed, thanks to the fantastic work of our core team,

504
00:28:54,904 --> 00:28:57,966
it allows us to get in high-quality large-scale simulations more quickly.

505
00:28:59,367 --> 00:29:03,490
And a large part of why we developed this is because spectacle is overall very important to the game.

506
00:29:03,490 --> 00:29:10,257
So a really good example of this new pipeline comes in from our bridge trailer and also our bridge mission.

507
00:29:10,257 --> 00:29:14,721
So this particular sequence is in the bridge mission.

508
00:29:14,721 --> 00:29:19,185
It's when the bridge kind of comes down and miles in this sequence is

509
00:29:20,045 --> 00:29:23,686
It's really sort of a moment where he develops himself as a hero.

510
00:29:23,686 --> 00:29:29,827
And this particular simulation, this had over 250,000 vertices.

511
00:29:29,827 --> 00:29:32,628
And I was really proud of our art team for working on this,

512
00:29:32,628 --> 00:29:37,469
including Matthew Bennett, Jin Choi, and Alex Heligo.

513
00:29:37,469 --> 00:29:41,470
They were able to really push the next-gen fidelity and spectacle on this.

514
00:29:41,470 --> 00:29:46,751
Next, we're going to talk about one of the simulations that we did for our Winter Break mission.

515
00:29:46,751 --> 00:29:48,832
This is actually the opening mission to the game.

516
00:29:49,612 --> 00:29:54,875
This particular sequence was a really good example of using both of our new simulation pipelines.

517
00:29:54,875 --> 00:29:59,677
So this includes both the rigid body atom chunk pipeline that we just talked about,

518
00:29:59,677 --> 00:30:03,339
as well as our soft body atom vert pipeline.

519
00:30:03,339 --> 00:30:10,003
So the soft body can really be seen on the streamers that fall down from this happy holiday sign,

520
00:30:10,003 --> 00:30:15,706
as well as the atom vert can really be kind of seen on those chunks of the sign as it comes down.

521
00:30:16,666 --> 00:30:22,248
One thing that was really great about this sequence was that we were able to push the

522
00:30:22,248 --> 00:30:29,111
fidelity in terms of sparks and debris particulate coming out in this sequence.

523
00:30:30,719 --> 00:30:35,424
on the PlayStation 5 even more so than we could on the PlayStation 4.

524
00:30:35,424 --> 00:30:39,508
And this was a kind of a really great place where we were able to really leverage that hardware

525
00:30:39,508 --> 00:30:46,354
in terms of creating that spectacle. And then another sequence that I thought was really great

526
00:30:46,354 --> 00:30:49,998
that we were able to really push for next gen is a sequence where this power plant explodes.

527
00:30:51,219 --> 00:30:56,622
The next-gen hardware afforded us the ability to have more particles, as well as shadow

528
00:30:56,622 --> 00:30:57,442
casting lights.

529
00:30:57,442 --> 00:31:01,524
If you look at some of the lights on these explosions on the ground, especially in this

530
00:31:01,524 --> 00:31:04,566
part right here, it really added a lot of drama.

531
00:31:04,566 --> 00:31:07,908
And the next-generation hardware was a place where we could really allow that to shine.

532
00:31:09,407 --> 00:31:17,236
Next, I'm going to talk about Programmable Matter, which is essentially the energy weapons

533
00:31:17,236 --> 00:31:20,739
that Miles' nemeses, the Underground, use in their game.

534
00:31:20,739 --> 00:31:25,605
So with Programmable Matter, Miles Morales, as a hero, we kind of needed to give him a

535
00:31:25,605 --> 00:31:29,369
really new enemy in order to complement him as an explosive new Spider-Man.

536
00:31:30,270 --> 00:31:32,493
So this is where the Tinker and the Underground come in.

537
00:31:32,493 --> 00:31:37,501
They used nanoparticle-driven weapon tech called programmable matter in the game.

538
00:31:37,501 --> 00:31:41,167
And of course, we as VFX artists had to come up with a solution for that.

539
00:31:41,678 --> 00:31:45,742
So we had to come up with new and different effects systems to be able to support this,

540
00:31:45,742 --> 00:31:49,365
to make it unique and different from what we accomplished in the original Marvel's Spider-Man.

541
00:31:49,365 --> 00:31:55,089
So one of the first things that we did when we were working on programmable matter was come up

542
00:31:55,089 --> 00:32:00,374
with a list of rules for it, so that we sort of understood what it was and how it worked.

543
00:32:00,374 --> 00:32:04,097
So we decided that programmable matter required nanotech printing.

544
00:32:05,438 --> 00:32:09,300
It formed an internal lattice, so it had a support structure inside of it as it printed.

545
00:32:09,300 --> 00:32:15,864
It was always printed from a source, so this never came from the air, it wasn't magical,

546
00:32:15,864 --> 00:32:20,607
it was always something that was tangible and came from a specific place.

547
00:32:20,607 --> 00:32:26,730
It is technically a metal, so programmable matter, it is metallic, it's not plastic,

548
00:32:26,730 --> 00:32:29,192
it has metallic properties to it.

549
00:32:29,872 --> 00:32:34,276
And it's always created by Finn Mason, who's the tinkerer in our game.

550
00:32:34,276 --> 00:32:38,979
So this was an early pre-visualization of programmable matter that we did to sort of

551
00:32:38,979 --> 00:32:41,501
help us cement what this looked like.

552
00:32:41,501 --> 00:32:43,403
And originally, programmable matter was green.

553
00:32:43,403 --> 00:32:47,486
Of course, we ended up changing the colors while we were working on it.

554
00:32:47,486 --> 00:32:50,909
But this kind of demonstrates some of those early principles that we came up with.

555
00:32:51,689 --> 00:32:57,450
for this. So you can kind of see it, it comes from a source, it creates an internal support structure as it prints.

556
00:32:57,450 --> 00:33:05,572
You can kind of see the particulate sort of spread over it as it comes into its final shape.

557
00:33:05,572 --> 00:33:11,933
And this was a really kind of a great guiding pre-visualization for us as we work to translate this into real time.

558
00:33:11,933 --> 00:33:16,153
One thing that we wanted to leverage when we were working with this was GPU particles,

559
00:33:16,153 --> 00:33:19,674
which is something that we didn't have on the original Marvel's Spider-Man.

560
00:33:20,914 --> 00:33:24,515
So this is kind of what we had in game in the end.

561
00:33:24,515 --> 00:33:30,376
So you can kind of see that a lot of that original pre-visualization made it into the game.

562
00:33:30,376 --> 00:33:35,897
So we do have that internal structure that kind of prints using a material graph

563
00:33:35,897 --> 00:33:41,598
that is followed by support struts on the inside, which kind of prints the skin on top.

564
00:33:41,598 --> 00:33:46,199
We leverage a lot of GPU particles with a little bit of noise on them to kind of help.

565
00:33:46,779 --> 00:33:48,460
fill everything in at the end.

566
00:33:48,460 --> 00:33:52,323
And then, of course, we also use particle lights

567
00:33:52,323 --> 00:33:54,284
just to sort of make sure that everything kind of ties

568
00:33:54,284 --> 00:33:56,346
into the scene correctly.

569
00:33:56,346 --> 00:34:04,751
So the inside of the programmable ladder lattice

570
00:34:04,751 --> 00:34:08,794
is controlled sort of like a material wipe.

571
00:34:08,794 --> 00:34:11,556
This is driven much like we drove our sleeves.

572
00:34:11,556 --> 00:34:13,517
So this is driven with a wipe that

573
00:34:13,517 --> 00:34:15,699
is controlled by vertex colors defined in Maya.

574
00:34:16,519 --> 00:34:18,961
And we use a lot more geometry for detail.

575
00:34:18,961 --> 00:34:23,344
So one big thing about next gen is that, you know, you can use more vertices

576
00:34:23,344 --> 00:34:27,686
and leveraging vertex wipes really allows you that precision to kind of give you

577
00:34:27,686 --> 00:34:31,809
that really controlled sort of look you're looking for, especially in

578
00:34:31,809 --> 00:34:35,531
any kind of cinematic beat where you really want to have control over that.

579
00:34:36,608 --> 00:34:41,671
The inside of these lattice models also contained an additional mesh.

580
00:34:41,671 --> 00:34:48,634
So these were sort of the interior lattices that went inside of each of those segments

581
00:34:48,634 --> 00:34:52,917
as they sort of snapped into place. And we use this in the cinematic as well as the gameplay

582
00:34:52,917 --> 00:34:57,599
versions. So a lot of segments are sort of driven with the same sort of technique where you have

583
00:34:57,599 --> 00:35:00,621
the vertex colors controlling a precise wipe.

584
00:35:01,583 --> 00:35:04,546
And then when it comes to timing that,

585
00:35:04,546 --> 00:35:06,748
this is just sort of a custom input value.

586
00:35:06,748 --> 00:35:09,411
So we have the x in that custom input node.

587
00:35:09,411 --> 00:35:11,833
That is something that is exposed to us

588
00:35:11,833 --> 00:35:14,336
and that we can manipulate and control and keyframe

589
00:35:14,336 --> 00:35:16,218
in the particle editor.

590
00:35:16,218 --> 00:35:20,462
So we use custom input values quite a bit while we work,

591
00:35:20,462 --> 00:35:22,464
because it gives us more precise control

592
00:35:22,464 --> 00:35:24,366
over the timing of when those come online.

593
00:35:25,881 --> 00:35:29,003
Another thing that we used quite a bit was GPU particles.

594
00:35:29,003 --> 00:35:32,827
So a lot of the underground attacks are driven by GPU particles.

595
00:35:32,827 --> 00:35:36,951
So you can kind of see, this is the gauntlet enemy's AoE impact.

596
00:35:36,951 --> 00:35:41,134
When the enemy hits the ground, it creates this awesome shape.

597
00:35:41,134 --> 00:35:44,377
They actually destroy their programmable matter technology as they do this.

598
00:35:44,998 --> 00:35:51,620
So GBA particles were new to Miles Morales since we had a CPU driven system only in the first Marvel Spider-Man.

599
00:35:51,620 --> 00:35:56,622
So because this was new technology, we really wanted, well new to our game engine,

600
00:35:56,622 --> 00:35:59,583
because it's something we hadn't had previously.

601
00:35:59,583 --> 00:36:03,805
We leveraged it heavily when it comes to the underground attacks.

602
00:36:04,671 --> 00:36:10,015
And we use them to help Parabola Matter feel more threatening and unique and different.

603
00:36:10,015 --> 00:36:13,497
So this is the main gauntlet enemy attack.

604
00:36:13,497 --> 00:36:17,020
You can kind of see that he jumps up in the air and he punches the ground.

605
00:36:17,020 --> 00:36:22,584
He breaks his gauntlet mesh and he reprints it using one of those detailed material wipes.

606
00:36:22,584 --> 00:36:29,068
And another thing that we used in here, if you look at this you can kind of see that it has a mesh that distorts

607
00:36:29,068 --> 00:36:33,011
and it creates some really awesome looking shapes as it...

608
00:36:33,632 --> 00:36:41,418
spreads out as a shockwave. And it's really using GPU particles in this instance helped to make it

609
00:36:41,418 --> 00:36:46,722
feel a lot more unique versus what we had in our previous game. Next I want to talk about webs.

610
00:36:46,722 --> 00:36:50,785
You can't really have Spider-Man without webs, so I thought it would be important to talk about that.

611
00:36:50,785 --> 00:36:55,368
So with webs, webs are one of the things that make Spider-Man, Spider-Man.

612
00:36:55,368 --> 00:36:58,851
Peter and Miles share webs, and we didn't really change these much from Marvel's Spider-Man.

613
00:36:59,735 --> 00:37:02,438
However, it's still kind of worth reviewing how we did it.

614
00:37:02,438 --> 00:37:05,061
Webs are a team effort between VFX and many other departments,

615
00:37:05,061 --> 00:37:08,806
including animation, rigging, rendering, and gameplay.

616
00:37:08,806 --> 00:37:11,369
And it's one of the things that we get asked about the most.

617
00:37:11,369 --> 00:37:13,952
So I wanted to make sure that I included it in this talk.

618
00:37:13,952 --> 00:37:16,314
So the first thing I want to talk about

619
00:37:16,314 --> 00:37:17,576
are the traversal webs.

620
00:37:17,576 --> 00:37:18,657
So these are the webs that

621
00:37:19,458 --> 00:37:22,019
Miles uses when he's swinging across the city.

622
00:37:22,019 --> 00:37:26,422
So you can kind of see here, this is in the bridge mission where he's swinging around.

623
00:37:26,422 --> 00:37:31,945
It's basically just those web lines that he uses to get all over the place.

624
00:37:31,945 --> 00:37:36,548
These are basically splines. They're programmatic in nature.

625
00:37:37,348 --> 00:37:42,270
On the effects team, what we do is we control the shader material that goes over the webs,

626
00:37:42,270 --> 00:37:46,531
as well as the web knots that are placed over the spline.

627
00:37:46,531 --> 00:37:51,073
So with the traversal webs, the knots are basically meshes that are placed procedurally

628
00:37:51,073 --> 00:37:53,654
across that spline.

629
00:37:53,654 --> 00:37:56,194
And then the webline itself is programmatic.

630
00:37:56,194 --> 00:38:01,296
So we didn't really adjust this much from Marvel's Spider-Man, but I still think it's

631
00:38:01,296 --> 00:38:02,817
a pretty cool system and worth talking about.

632
00:38:03,958 --> 00:38:07,100
Another web system I wanted to talk about are the web jackets.

633
00:38:07,100 --> 00:38:11,061
So these are webs that the players can put on enemies during gameplay.

634
00:38:11,061 --> 00:38:12,882
They serve a function in gameplay.

635
00:38:12,882 --> 00:38:15,403
They allow the player to immobilize enemies.

636
00:38:15,403 --> 00:38:20,445
And essentially because they are webs, they do need to be skin tight to fit over the character.

637
00:38:20,845 --> 00:38:24,586
So with these kinds of webs, we have face webs as well as the body webs.

638
00:38:24,586 --> 00:38:29,208
Each of these kinds of webs are skinned in Maya to each character model.

639
00:38:29,208 --> 00:38:31,909
So we have to get that character in the proper bind pose,

640
00:38:31,909 --> 00:38:36,150
and then we create layers of meshes over it.

641
00:38:36,150 --> 00:38:41,672
We do have our meshes set up in such a way that they play nicely with the UVs and materials

642
00:38:41,672 --> 00:38:43,253
in our engine for webs.

643
00:38:43,253 --> 00:38:47,814
And the materials for the webs, they basically drive the terrain and the appearance.

644
00:38:47,814 --> 00:38:50,275
So when these go on and off, they kind of erode in and out.

645
00:38:50,819 --> 00:38:52,374
A lot of that is material-driven.

646
00:38:53,476 --> 00:38:56,778
Next, I wanted to talk about the Stick Stuff Together web.

647
00:38:56,778 --> 00:38:59,520
So these are the web cones and web tunnels.

648
00:38:59,520 --> 00:39:01,241
You can kind of see them here where

649
00:39:01,241 --> 00:39:05,023
Miles is trying to stop this bus from going over the bridge.

650
00:39:05,023 --> 00:39:08,125
He places a number of web tunnels on the bus.

651
00:39:08,125 --> 00:39:10,826
And these are, we kind of call them Stick Stuff Together

652
00:39:10,826 --> 00:39:13,428
webs, but they're really sort of a collaborative effort

653
00:39:13,428 --> 00:39:14,749
between departments.

654
00:39:14,749 --> 00:39:17,550
When we create these, they're modeled in Maya

655
00:39:17,550 --> 00:39:20,232
using a custom tool set up for creating them.

656
00:39:21,151 --> 00:39:24,994
And the materials are then applied in engine to these.

657
00:39:24,994 --> 00:39:27,717
And after that, they're rigged and animated

658
00:39:27,717 --> 00:39:30,459
by our tech animation and animation department.

659
00:39:30,459 --> 00:39:32,541
So on the effects side, a lot of what we do

660
00:39:32,541 --> 00:39:35,604
is mostly just generating the initial meshes

661
00:39:35,604 --> 00:39:38,607
and then we'll generate the materials that go with it.

662
00:39:38,607 --> 00:39:41,089
However, when it comes to controlling them

663
00:39:41,089 --> 00:39:42,330
and animating them and placing them,

664
00:39:42,330 --> 00:39:45,393
a lot of that is done by our animation team.

665
00:39:45,393 --> 00:39:46,854
And webs are really a team effort.

666
00:39:48,252 --> 00:39:51,213
So something that I thought was really important to touch on

667
00:39:51,213 --> 00:39:54,214
in this talk was accessibility.

668
00:39:54,214 --> 00:39:55,995
Accessibility was very important for us

669
00:39:55,995 --> 00:39:57,376
for Next Generation.

670
00:39:57,376 --> 00:40:00,137
And at Insomnia Games, we had a really big push

671
00:40:00,137 --> 00:40:02,097
to create the most accessible game possible.

672
00:40:02,097 --> 00:40:04,118
So many departments, including visual effects,

673
00:40:04,118 --> 00:40:06,459
decided to pitch in and see what we could do

674
00:40:06,459 --> 00:40:08,700
to make this game one of the most accessible games

675
00:40:08,700 --> 00:40:09,340
we've ever made.

676
00:40:10,692 --> 00:40:13,935
So we had this philosophy of anyone can wear the mask.

677
00:40:13,935 --> 00:40:16,938
Basically, we thought anyone should be able to be Spider-Man.

678
00:40:16,938 --> 00:40:21,061
And we wanted as many players as possible to enjoy that fantasy of being Spider-Man.

679
00:40:21,061 --> 00:40:25,425
So released within the effects team, we sort of drove what we called contrast

680
00:40:25,425 --> 00:40:28,107
features in Marvel's Spider-Man Miles Morales.

681
00:40:28,107 --> 00:40:31,250
And we found that we could have a really big impact on the game in this way.

682
00:40:31,250 --> 00:40:33,972
And I'll get into what contrast features are in a second.

683
00:40:34,092 --> 00:40:37,697
One of the things that we created for this was the high contrast background.

684
00:40:37,697 --> 00:40:40,740
So that is designed to help low vision players enjoy our game.

685
00:40:40,740 --> 00:40:45,386
This is essentially a full screen quad that we put over the screen that desaturates the world.

686
00:40:45,386 --> 00:40:51,494
And then after we desaturate the world, we'll flag relevant effects for combat to draw on top of that full screen quad.

687
00:40:52,295 --> 00:41:00,044
And we'll also add high contrast shaders to enemies and combatants and relevant objects to gameplay in order to help them stand out.

688
00:41:00,044 --> 00:41:02,046
And this is kind of what that looks like in action.

689
00:41:02,046 --> 00:41:06,431
This is, you can kind of see the skybox is darkened, the enemies get bright shaders.

690
00:41:07,260 --> 00:41:15,247
relevant effects to the combat, drawn on top of that background. So this is a really beneficial

691
00:41:15,247 --> 00:41:21,933
mode for anybody who has vision issues, anybody that might have cognitive issues. They might

692
00:41:21,933 --> 00:41:26,477
benefit from this because it basically reduces visual clutter and visual noise and it tells the

693
00:41:26,477 --> 00:41:26,817
player...

694
00:41:27,858 --> 00:41:33,000
you know, what is important for them in combat. And we found that this was very helpful for a

695
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:37,181
variety of players. And part of why this is so important, I'm going to get a little personal

696
00:41:37,181 --> 00:41:44,424
with this, but this is a video from the original Marvel's Spider-Man, and this is the Fisk boss

697
00:41:44,424 --> 00:41:45,624
fight. So this is the first.

698
00:41:46,164 --> 00:41:47,885
boss fight in that game.

699
00:41:47,885 --> 00:41:51,106
And my fiance is a low vision player.

700
00:41:51,106 --> 00:41:54,648
And when he played through this segment of the game, when I went to watch him

701
00:41:54,648 --> 00:41:58,129
play it at home, he was unable to get through this segment of the boss fight.

702
00:41:58,129 --> 00:42:03,352
And the reason for that was because he was unable to tell the difference

703
00:42:03,352 --> 00:42:04,692
between the boss and the ads.

704
00:42:05,893 --> 00:42:09,515
And looking at this as a visual effects artist, I know this is a problem that we can solve,

705
00:42:09,515 --> 00:42:14,939
especially as a real-time effects community. I think that it's something that pretty much

706
00:42:14,939 --> 00:42:22,043
anybody could come up with a solution for. So the solution that, well, this is just sort of

707
00:42:22,043 --> 00:42:27,667
a simulation of what that low vision looks like. So this is actually a simulation I did of my

708
00:42:27,667 --> 00:42:31,149
fiancé's sight. So he's losing some of his central vision.

709
00:42:31,569 --> 00:42:35,991
So for a low vision player, you can imagine it's very frustrating when you're playing in a fight like this.

710
00:42:35,991 --> 00:42:40,132
You're not able to really tell who's the boss and who the adds are.

711
00:42:40,132 --> 00:42:44,414
But thanks to the contrast features that we added to Marvel's Spider-Man Miles Morales,

712
00:42:44,414 --> 00:42:49,936
my fiancé, I'm glad to report, was able to play through that game entirely by himself without assistance.

713
00:42:49,936 --> 00:42:52,877
And part of that was because of these contrast features that we added.

714
00:42:53,277 --> 00:42:58,341
And at least for me personally, I think this is probably one of the things that I thought was the

715
00:42:58,341 --> 00:43:03,526
coolest part of creating a next generation title, was really thinking holistically about game

716
00:43:03,526 --> 00:43:08,170
development and thinking about ways that we can make games more accessible than ever to new players.

717
00:43:08,170 --> 00:43:11,112
And honestly, this is probably one of the things I'm most proud of.

718
00:43:11,873 --> 00:43:18,358
So one of the tricks that we did for the high contrast background was basically making the

719
00:43:18,358 --> 00:43:22,580
skybox really dark. So in order to detect the skybox so that you can color it something other

720
00:43:22,580 --> 00:43:27,183
than skybox colored, you just have to compare the depth buffer to the far clip value and you can

721
00:43:27,183 --> 00:43:31,966
just do a lerp really easy. That darkens the skybox while keeping the foreground intact.

722
00:43:33,287 --> 00:43:37,169
So another thing that we did for this title was develop contrast shaders.

723
00:43:37,169 --> 00:43:41,352
So the contrast shaders are designed to be bright and easy to spot for low vision players.

724
00:43:41,352 --> 00:43:49,116
They're also customizable, so players can select different colors for ranged enemies versus melee enemies versus bosses.

725
00:43:49,116 --> 00:43:53,678
And it's really important to us, at least for our game, that players are able to distinguish those.

726
00:43:53,678 --> 00:43:57,060
Of course, everybody might have a different solution for their own titles.

727
00:43:57,060 --> 00:43:58,561
It worked for us in Spider-Man.

728
00:43:58,921 --> 00:44:01,602
might not work for every game out there.

729
00:44:01,602 --> 00:44:03,784
So hopefully you can kind of look at this

730
00:44:03,784 --> 00:44:06,025
and think about ways that you could develop a similar mode

731
00:44:06,025 --> 00:44:08,066
for your own game.

732
00:44:08,066 --> 00:44:10,447
So the contrast shaders are sort of set up in a config file.

733
00:44:10,447 --> 00:44:12,809
And this is driven by our gameplay team,

734
00:44:12,809 --> 00:44:15,290
who is wonderful and set this up for us.

735
00:44:15,290 --> 00:44:19,632
And this ties into our UI for easy player customization.

736
00:44:19,632 --> 00:44:22,474
It was really important for us that the players

737
00:44:22,474 --> 00:44:24,835
were able to pick different colors

738
00:44:24,835 --> 00:44:26,256
and customize their experience.

739
00:44:28,089 --> 00:44:31,572
So lastly, I'm going to talk about some of the challenges we encountered for the new generation

740
00:44:31,572 --> 00:44:34,855
and some of the takeaways and learnings that we had.

741
00:44:34,855 --> 00:44:41,821
So some of the challenges that we faced with this title was that Marvel's Spider-Man Miles Morales

742
00:44:41,821 --> 00:44:46,064
really needed to be a next-gen title while also at the same time being a cross-platform title.

743
00:44:46,064 --> 00:44:47,205
It had to release on the PS4, too.

744
00:44:47,205 --> 00:44:51,709
So one of the challenges we had was how can we make a game perform on PS4

745
00:44:51,709 --> 00:44:54,151
while still finding ways to push next-gen quality?

746
00:44:54,712 --> 00:45:00,876
One of the solutions that we came up with that was, I think, really helpful was that within our internal editor,

747
00:45:00,876 --> 00:45:04,878
we basically set it up so that we could split some of the particle emitters per platform.

748
00:45:04,878 --> 00:45:10,402
So in this example, this is actually a smoke emitter, and the smoke emitter is flagged to be PS5 only,

749
00:45:10,402 --> 00:45:15,626
and that's because we wanted this particular smoke to cast shadows, and it's disabled on the PS4.

750
00:45:15,626 --> 00:45:21,209
And there is a similar PS4-only emitter within this effects package that doesn't have shadows on it.

751
00:45:21,810 --> 00:45:27,335
So this was a great solution for us to be cost effective in terms of not needing to re-implement

752
00:45:27,335 --> 00:45:29,116
some of these emitters multiple times.

753
00:45:29,116 --> 00:45:33,960
And it really helped us out in terms of delivering that next-gen quality.

754
00:45:33,960 --> 00:45:39,025
So with this system, with the PS4, PS5 emitters, it allowed us to selectively add a bunch of

755
00:45:39,025 --> 00:45:43,689
particle upgrades for the PS5 that might have been unperforming on the PS4.

756
00:45:44,530 --> 00:45:47,134
Some of those included making more of our particles lit.

757
00:45:47,134 --> 00:45:50,098
We were able to afford more particle lighting

758
00:45:50,098 --> 00:45:53,303
on this generation, which definitely added more drama

759
00:45:53,303 --> 00:45:54,685
to our effects.

760
00:45:54,685 --> 00:45:57,409
More shadow casting particles, so those large columns of steam,

761
00:45:57,409 --> 00:45:59,572
we were able to have those cast shadows.

762
00:46:00,472 --> 00:46:02,713
We were also able to have more shadow casting particle lights.

763
00:46:02,713 --> 00:46:09,858
So those are for instances when you want to have a light inside of an effects package that casts a shadow.

764
00:46:09,858 --> 00:46:13,941
We could afford more of those and switch between the PS4 and the PS5.

765
00:46:13,941 --> 00:46:16,183
We were able to afford denser smoke and fires.

766
00:46:16,183 --> 00:46:19,245
So, you know, in order to get things performing on the PS4,

767
00:46:19,245 --> 00:46:22,868
sometimes we couldn't afford quite as many embers or smoke as we wanted to,

768
00:46:22,868 --> 00:46:24,569
whereas on the PS5 we could afford more.

769
00:46:24,569 --> 00:46:27,111
So we leveraged that system in those cases.

770
00:46:27,424 --> 00:46:30,458
And we can also afford more GPU particles in some instances,

771
00:46:30,458 --> 00:46:31,664
which was wonderful.

772
00:46:32,806 --> 00:46:34,667
Some other limitations that we ran into,

773
00:46:34,667 --> 00:46:38,649
the PS4 had more memory limits compared to PS5.

774
00:46:38,649 --> 00:46:40,691
Part of that meant that simulations had to be smaller

775
00:46:40,691 --> 00:46:42,892
for the PlayStation 4, unfortunately.

776
00:46:42,892 --> 00:46:45,954
We were able to afford more on the PlayStation 5.

777
00:46:45,954 --> 00:46:48,456
Text to memory was more of a concern on the PlayStation 4,

778
00:46:48,456 --> 00:46:52,439
so we were limited to how many smoke maps we could use

779
00:46:52,439 --> 00:46:55,661
on that console versus how many variety of maps

780
00:46:55,661 --> 00:46:57,282
we could use on the PlayStation 5.

781
00:46:58,102 --> 00:47:01,165
Loading times were also something we had to be mindful of.

782
00:47:01,165 --> 00:47:03,767
So the PlayStation 5's solid state drive

783
00:47:03,767 --> 00:47:05,829
meant that we were able to load scenes very fast.

784
00:47:05,829 --> 00:47:08,631
Unfortunately on the PlayStation 4,

785
00:47:08,631 --> 00:47:11,994
we had to preload in simulations a little bit earlier

786
00:47:11,994 --> 00:47:14,396
just so that we could have that play correctly on time.

787
00:47:15,688 --> 00:47:20,712
Some other findings, the PlayStation 5, it had more memory in the solid-state drive,

788
00:47:20,712 --> 00:47:24,375
so that was a huge advantage. So we were able to load in our simulations very quickly on that platform.

789
00:47:24,375 --> 00:47:30,160
The GPU, it definitely needed more space for ray tracing. So one finding was that although we could

790
00:47:30,160 --> 00:47:34,264
afford a little more GPU particles, that didn't mean that we could go crazy, right? You know,

791
00:47:34,264 --> 00:47:41,029
just because we have a great new hardware doesn't necessarily mean that we can, you know, go to 11

792
00:47:41,029 --> 00:47:42,210
with GPU particles.

793
00:47:43,121 --> 00:47:45,847
We also found that we still need to watch overdraw on next-gen,

794
00:47:45,847 --> 00:47:48,632
so alpha and overdraw is still going to be expensive.

795
00:47:48,632 --> 00:47:52,621
That's one of the reasons why leveraging meshes with negative space worked out so well for us.

796
00:47:53,904 --> 00:47:58,566
And one of the big wins was that we could afford more vertices on the PlayStation 5

797
00:47:58,566 --> 00:47:59,606
versus the PlayStation 4.

798
00:47:59,606 --> 00:48:03,728
And that was a huge benefit that we definitely leveraged.

799
00:48:03,728 --> 00:48:07,269
And that allowed us to use more meshes where it made sense.

800
00:48:07,269 --> 00:48:09,690
However, we still had to be careful to watch vertex density.

801
00:48:09,690 --> 00:48:15,252
So whenever we had really small splashes, we couldn't put 10,000 verts on something like that.

802
00:48:15,252 --> 00:48:20,593
We still had to be somewhat mindful of how dense the vertices got.

803
00:48:22,045 --> 00:48:28,168
So some general learnings from working on this project, just the non-technical learnings.

804
00:48:28,168 --> 00:48:33,171
The ambition of NextGen was a little nerve-wracking, but one of the big takeaways for me was that

805
00:48:33,171 --> 00:48:37,333
you can't create great things if you don't try, and it's definitely okay to be a little

806
00:48:37,333 --> 00:48:38,213
nervous.

807
00:48:38,213 --> 00:48:42,415
When you're feeling a little nervous, it means that you're on the right track and you're

808
00:48:42,415 --> 00:48:44,756
going outside of your comfort zone and making something wonderful.

809
00:48:45,820 --> 00:48:51,386
An example of this is when we had to build our Annenverte pipeline to make that reveal shot a reality.

810
00:48:51,386 --> 00:48:56,472
Because the simulation, it was really important that we saw the fabric tear away so we could reveal who Miles was.

811
00:48:56,472 --> 00:49:02,539
And if we hadn't really taken that leap of faith, I don't think we would have made a shot as great as that shot was.

812
00:49:02,539 --> 00:49:06,003
And we wouldn't have developed this wonderful new pipeline that we can use in our engine.

813
00:49:07,004 --> 00:49:11,008
We also took a chance on accessibility features, and we delivered a much more accessible game.

814
00:49:11,008 --> 00:49:16,252
So one thing that was really wonderful working on this title is that, you know, I didn't really go

815
00:49:16,252 --> 00:49:19,455
into this title thinking that, you know, it was going to be the most accessible game ever, but

816
00:49:19,455 --> 00:49:23,598
the more passionate we got about it, the more excited we got about accessibility,

817
00:49:23,598 --> 00:49:28,262
and the more the studio rallied behind creating the most accessible game we could.

818
00:49:28,262 --> 00:49:31,245
I feel like we really kind of pulled together and made something great.

819
00:49:31,765 --> 00:49:35,908
And it was really personally satisfying to see someone I care about be able to play through

820
00:49:35,908 --> 00:49:40,852
the game from start to finish by himself, even though he is a low vision player.

821
00:49:40,852 --> 00:49:45,775
And one of the benefits of this too is that we found all kinds of players, not necessarily

822
00:49:45,775 --> 00:49:48,137
just low vision ones, benefited from the contrast options.

823
00:49:49,131 --> 00:49:52,375
We were also able to give Miles his own unique powers that were different from Peter's through

824
00:49:52,375 --> 00:49:57,182
visual effects. So it was really wonderful to be able to tell that story and to tell that narrative

825
00:49:57,182 --> 00:50:01,588
of Miles becoming his own hero and Miles having his own experiences through visuals.

826
00:50:03,306 --> 00:50:08,169
Some other additional learnings, when working on new hardware, old techniques can be leveraged

827
00:50:08,169 --> 00:50:09,990
in new ways.

828
00:50:09,990 --> 00:50:15,594
So using vertex blending with detailed color usage to drive material transitions.

829
00:50:15,594 --> 00:50:19,596
So we were able to leverage more vertices and that was kind of new, but vertex painting,

830
00:50:19,596 --> 00:50:24,099
I mean that's kind of an old technique, but blending the old with the new was kind of

831
00:50:24,099 --> 00:50:25,920
a big discovery on this project.

832
00:50:26,807 --> 00:50:29,810
I also learned that it's really important to thank your programming team for

833
00:50:29,810 --> 00:50:33,573
all the amazing work that they do to enable you to push toward a new generation

834
00:50:33,573 --> 00:50:34,133
of greatness.

835
00:50:34,133 --> 00:50:37,315
So a lot of what we did and what we covered in this talk wouldn't have been

836
00:50:37,315 --> 00:50:39,497
possible without our wonderful programming staff.

837
00:50:39,497 --> 00:50:43,540
They really enabled the visual effects team to do their best and be their best.

838
00:50:44,220 --> 00:50:47,463
I also learned that over-communicating is good.

839
00:50:47,463 --> 00:50:52,528
On this project, we really had to rally together to create something wonderful.

840
00:50:52,528 --> 00:50:59,795
The more that we work together and problem-solve together, the better we were able to deliver

841
00:50:59,795 --> 00:51:00,936
this project.

842
00:51:01,787 --> 00:51:04,571
And lastly, you know, I really love this project.

843
00:51:04,571 --> 00:51:08,295
The people I worked with were some of the best in the industry,

844
00:51:08,295 --> 00:51:10,478
and I'm really proud of what we did together.

845
00:51:10,478 --> 00:51:14,543
And I'm really glad that I was able to talk with you all about

846
00:51:14,543 --> 00:51:17,386
the effects that we did for this game.

847
00:51:17,386 --> 00:51:19,549
And thank you very much. Let's have some Q&A.

